    "descripcionEn": "Rotator cuff injury encompasses a spectrum of pathologies affecting the group of four muscles and their tendons (supraspinatus, infraspinatus, teres minor, and subscapularis) that dynamically stabilize the glenohumeral joint and allow rotation and elevation movements of the shoulder. The supraspinatus is most frequently affected due to its vulnerable anatomical position in the subacromial space and its critical zone of hypovascularization. Injuries range from tendinopathy (tendinosis without tear) and partial tears (bursal surface, articular, or intratendinous) to full-thickness complete tears that may involve one or multiple tendons. This pathology is extraordinarily prevalent: MRI studies in asymptomatic individuals over 60 years show rotator cuff tears in 30-50% of cases, underscoring the importance of correlating imaging findings with clinical presentation. In the sports context, it is especially frequent in overhead athletes such as swimmers, tennis players, volleyball players, baseball players, and javelin throwers.",
